A '''dummy purchaser''' is an [[Agent (law)|agent]] who buys property on behalf of another, usually to conceal the true purpose of the acquisition. For instance, a shopping mall developer may hire a dummy buyer to purchase the needed vacant lots. Disclosing the principal's identity might prompt the landowners to hold out for a higher price; hence the need for secrecy. It has been hypothesized that dummy buyers could help private sector developers obtain the land needed for highway construction without the need for [[eminent domain]] invocation.<ref>{{cite book|title=Street Smart: Competition, Entrepreneurship, and the Future of Roads|chapter=Do Holdout Problems Justify Compulsory Right-of-Way Purchase|pages=48|author=Benson, Bruce L.|year=2006}}</ref> A principal in such a relationship may be a [[partially disclosed principal]] (i.e. the agent informs the seller that he is buying on behalf of someone, but does not reveal that person's identity) or a completely [[undisclosed principal]] (i.e. the agent does not reveal that he is acting on anyone's behalf). A dummy purchaser is also sometimes called a [[Straw man (law)|straw man]].<ref>[http://www.rickseiler.com/SeilerSchoolOfRealEstate/IndependentStudy/Glossary.htm Glossary<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
==Dummying== In [[Australia]], during periods of conversion of Government land to freehold or leasehold, the practice (also called "dummyism") of wealthy [[Squatting (pastoral)|squatters]] employing someone who qualifies as a "[[Squatting (pastoral)#Legislation to allow selection|free selector]]" to acquire land that they themselves would not have access to.<ref>Ramson, W. S. (ed.) ''The Australian National Dictionary'' Oxford University Press, Melbourne 1988 p.225 {{ISBN|0 19 554736 5}} </ref> This practice was particularly useful in acquiring or denying to others access to watercourses and thoroughfares.
==See also== *[[Straw man (law)]]
